Primal TCG Comprehensive Rules Version 1.3.0

This rulebook provides a comprehensive explanation of the rules and mechanics of Primal TCG. It is intended to assist in navigating complex scenarios and interactions for players who are already familiar with the basic rules.

The contents of this document include:  
A Table of Contents  
A breakdown of the game sectioned and subsections  
A glossary

Revisions to this document may have been made since its release. The most recent version of this document should always be used.

This document does not provide rules or instructions for games including 3 or more players.

# 1\. Universal Rules {#1.-universal-rules}

## 1.1. Rule Contradictions in Card Text {#1.1.-rule-contradictions-in-card-text}

When a card’s text contradicts the rules in this document, the card’s text takes precedence and the rules are ignored for that specific situation.

	*Example: A player uses a card that allows them to Summon an additional Character Card for the turn. The one Summon per turn limit of the rules is ignored, but only while the Effect of the card is applied.*

	**Exception: A player may concede the game to their opponent at any time, and this rule may not be prevented or modified by any other rule or card.**

## 1.2. Can’t Beats Can {#1.2.-can’t-beats-can}

When a card’s text states that something can’t happen, it takes precedence over the rules in this document as well as any other card.

	*Example: A player uses a card that allows them to Summon an additional character card for the turn, but another card in play states that they can’t Summon character cards at all. The player may not Summon Character cards.*

## 1.3. Impossible to Complete Actions (the “Do as Much as You Can” Rule) {#1.3.-impossible-to-complete-actions-(the-“do-as-much-as-you-can”-rule)}

If a card’s text directs a player to perform an action that is impossible to complete, that portion of the text is ignored and the rest of the text is performed as normal.  
	  
*Example: A card directs a player to Discard their Hand and afterward draw 1 card, but the player has no Hand of cards to Discard. The player directed to perform the Effect ignores the Discard part of the Effect and draws 1 card.*

	If a card’s text directs a player to perform an action that the player may only partially perform, that player performs as much of that action as possible.

	*Example: A card directs a player to Discard 2 cards from their Hand, but the player only has 1\. That player still Discards the 1 card in their hand, even though the direction was to Discard 2\.*

### 1.3.1 “And if you do” Clauses {#1.3.1-“and-if-you-do”-clauses}

If a card’s text directs a player to perform an action that is either impossible or only partially performable prior to the phrase “and if you do”, those instructions in that effect prior to “and if you do” are entirely conditional and the “Do as Much as You Can” rule does not apply. The effect’s instructions prior to “and if you do” must be completed in full. Any directions after “and if you do” still adhere to the “Do as Much as You Can” rule.

	*Example: A card directs a player to move two cards from that player’s hand to the bottom of their deck, and states if the player does, that player draws 2 cards. If the player only has 1 card in their hand, that player does not move any cards from their hand to the bottom of their deck and the direction to draw 2 cards is ignored.*

## 1.4. Card Ownership {#1.4.-card-ownership}

Each player is considered the Owner of every card in their deck at the start of the game. 

1. Ownership may not change.   
2. At the end of each game every card is returned to the Owner’s deck.

If a Card would Move to the Deck, Hand, Discard Pile, Expel Area, or Essence Area, it Moves to the owner’s respective zone instead regardless of where the card was previously. Cards moving to the Battle Reward Area follow this same rule with the exception that they may be Moved to either player’s Battle Reward Area if an Effect specifies.

# 2\. Requirements to Play {#2.-requirements-to-play}

## 2.1. Deck {#2.1.-deck}

Each player must have a 50-61 card deck consisting of 50-60 Character, Strategy, and Ability cards, as well as up to 1 Field card. Players must supply their own cards.

With the exception of only 1 Field card to include, players may include up to 3 copies of any card in their deck. Cards have a card number on the lower left-Hand corner for each card type. If two cards have different art or text, but the same set number, they are considered the same card for the purpose of deck construction.

Some cards might explicitly state if its inclusion in a deck has an exception to these rules.	

## 2.2. Tokens and Counters {#2.2.-tokens-and-counters}

Some cards require additional game pieces to represent tokens or Counters. It’s each player’s responsibility to understand and supply what additional pieces they will need to play.  
Official Primal TCG tokens and Counters are recommended, but when unavailable, dice and coins may be used.

### 2.2.1. Tokens  {#2.2.1.-tokens}

Tokens are representations of cards that are not included in a Deck but are produced by Effects. Tokens have official printed editions that define what they do, but may also be found on the Primal TCG App.  
    
If an In Play Token would Move to an area not In Play, that Token is removed from the game instead. 

1. Tokens may still be Discarded, Expelled, or Attached, but are removed from the game instead of moving to the area they would otherwise Move to.   
2. Effects that would activate due to a Token being Discarded, Expelled, or Attached still activate, but Effects that would activate due to a card being Moved to a specific game zone won’t.

### 2.2.2. Counters {#2.2.2.-counters}

Counters are placed on In Play cards for various applications:  
Permanent Counters are used to track how long Strategies may remain in play.  
\+1/+1 and \-1/-1 Counters modify stats of Characters.  
Other Counters may be named, defined, or used by Effects. Unless an Effect specifies what the Counter does, the Counter does nothing on its own but may still enable other Effects.

Counters may not be placed on cards that aren’t In Play. If a card with Counters on it Moves to an area not In Play, those Counters are removed from the game.

## 2.3. Turn Marker {#2.3.-turn-marker}

Primal TCG requires players to keep track of how many turns go by. Each player is required to supply a method of tracking their turn count in a way that is clear to both players at all times. Official Primal TCG playmats have a designated track for a small object like a coin to keep track, but dice also work.

Turn Markers may not be removed from the game and have no upper limit, but may not go below 0\.

# 3\. The Game Board {#3.-the-game-board}

![][image1]

## 3.1. In Play Areas (highlighted in red) {#3.1.-in-play-areas-(highlighted-in-red)}

Cards in the Kingdom, Battlefield and Field areas are all “In Play” (cards that are Attached to or otherwise placed underneath cards in these areas are not). Effects referring to In Play cards are always referring to cards in these areas, and other areas are not considered In Play under any circumstances. When a card moves to an In Play area from an area that isn’t In Play, that card is considered “Put in Play”. If an effect would intend to move a card from an out of play area to an In Play area, that effect is attempting to “Put in Play” a card.

## 3.2. Control of Cards {#3.2.-control-of-cards}

Players have Control of cards that are In Play on their side of the field. Control of a card may switch from one player to another, as long as that card remains In Play.

If a card under a player’s control uses an Effect that Moves itself to another area as any part of its Effect or Cost, that player still controls and resolves the Effect of that card even if the card Moves to another player’s game board.

If a card under a player’s control specifies moving itself to a specific player’s area (using wording such as “your” or “your opponent’s”) as any part of its Effect or Cost, that Effect may still be activated and resolved as though it went to the correct area even though cards always Move to the owner’s respective area if it isn’t In Play. However, if an Effect specifies moving to a specific area and is followed by “and if you do”, the remainder of the Effect may not be applied if the card does not Move to the appropriate area.

If a card uses an Effect that may only be used once per turn and later in the turn changes control to another player, that card may not use its Effect again until the next turn.

## 3.3. Public and Private Information {#3.3.-public-and-private-information}

With the exception of each player’s Hand which is often picked up and set down, cards on the game board are either face-up and Public Information or face-down and Private Information. 

When a card is considered Public Information, both players are permitted to pick up and read what that card is and does.

When a card is considered Private Information, neither player may look at it unless an Effect tells them to. The order of any Private cards in any area is always considered to be random.   
If an Effect instructs a player to look at face down cards in a way that reveals their order in full, those cards are always re-randomized afterward unless the Effect explicitly tells a player to keep the order the same.  
	  
*Example A: A player uses an Effect that instructs them to search through their deck for a specific card and add it to their Hand. The Effect doesn’t state that their deck is shuffled afterward, but since the player now knows the order of their deck, the deck is shuffled.*   
*The same would be applied if the Effect directed a player to search through their Battle Rewards.*

	*Example B: A player uses an Effect that instructs them to look at the top 5 cards of their deck, add one of them to their Hand, then Discard the remaining cards. The deck is not shuffled afterward unless the Effect explicitly states to, as the order of the remaining cards in the deck is still unknown to either player.*

	When an Effect directs a player to search through a Private Area for a specific card, that player may claim that they do not want to select one that meets the specifications of the Effect, even if one is available. In that case, the action directed to be performed with the searched card is not performed. Players do not need to prove that they are unable to select a legal card when they do so and may search for a card successfully if the same search effect is used again later in the game.

	*Example: A player uses 0036 Collateral Damage to search their deck for a Plasma or Fire Character card with a Turn Cost of 1 or less. While searching their deck, they decide that they would prefer not to add any of the selectable cards from their deck to their hand. They declare that they are not selecting anything, add nothing to their hand, then shuffle their deck.*

## 3.4. Areas (labeled in graphic above) {#3.4.-areas-(labeled-in-graphic-above)}

1. ### Field Area {#field-area}

Field cards are placed here face-up at the beginning of the game.

1. Field cards are in-play and may not be removed from the game or Moved to other areas of the game board.

   

2. ### Battle Reward Area {#battle-reward-area}

When a player scores a Battle Reward (shortened to BR), cards are Moved from their opponent’s deck to the Battle Reward Area face-down. Since your opponent’s Battle Rewards are made from cards you own, they are placed on your side of the field, but the Battle Reward Area itself belongs to your opponent.

1. “Your Battle Rewards” refers to the Battle Rewards in your Battle Reward Area, which is on your opponent’s side of the field.   
2. “Your Opponent’s Battle Rewards” refers to the Battle Rewards in their Battle Reward Area, which is on your side of the field.  
3. After an effect instructs a player to look at a player’s Battle Rewards, those Battle Rewards are randomized and returned face down.  
   

3. ### Battlefield {#battlefield}

Character cards are Moved here face-up during the battle phase as organized Teams.

4. ### Kingdom {#kingdom}

Character and Permanent Strategy cards are played here face-up.

1. There is no maximum number of Character or Permanent Strategy cards in a Kingdom.

   

5. ### Essence Area {#essence-area}

Cards are either Moved to or from here face-up as Costs for Effects. 

1. Ability and Strategy cards go here after being played.  
2. Players may Move any number of cards from their Hand to the Essence Area as often as they like during their turn. This is referred to as “Charging” Essence.  
   1. Effects might Charge Essence from other game areas, but without an effect that allows for it, players may only Charge Essence with cards from their hand.  
3. When multiple cards are Moved from the Essence Area to pay for Costs (such as for Ability Cards) those cards are Moved simultaneously.

6. ### Turn Marker {#turn-marker}

A numerical indicator of each player’s turn, starting at 0 and moving up by 1 at the end of turn. Turn Markers are often referenced as a requirement for playing Character and Strategy cards.

1. Turn Markers are considered neither In-Play nor Out of Play.  
2. Official Primal TCG Playmats may feature a tracker for Turn Markers (shown in F).   
3. Dice are a suitable method for tracking Turn Markers as well as supplementing official trackers when displayed turn markers are exceeded.  
4. Turn Markers have no upper limit but cannot go below 0\.  
   

7. ### Discard pile (shortened to DP) {#discard-pile-(shortened-to-dp)}

Cards that are Discarded, spent for Effect Costs or otherwise Moved here are placed in the Discard pile face-up. 

1. How many and what cards are in the Discard pile is public information.  
2. When a card is Discarded, it is Moved to the Discard Pile, but when a card is Moved to the Discard Pile without using the word “Discarded”, it is not considered to be Discarded for the purposes of Effects.  
   

8. ### Deck {#deck}

Each Player’s deck is placed here face down. Decks should be randomized at the start of the game, and the order of the deck afterward shouldn’t be rearranged. 

1. Decks are only shuffled when an Effect directs a player to, or after a player searches through a deck in a way that would reveal the order of every card.  
2. The number of cards remaining in a deck is public information.  
3. When an Effect directs a player to Move, Discard, or otherwise access any number of cards in the deck, those cards are Moved, Discarded, or accessed simultaneously.

9. ### Expel Area {#expel-area}

Cards are Moved here face-up when they are Expelled. Similar in function to the Discard pile, but Expelled cards are more difficult to access. 

1. How many and what cards are in the Expel area is public information.   
2. When a card is Expelled, it is Moved to the Expel Area, but when a card is Moved to the Expel Area without using the word “Expel”, it is not considered to be Expelled for the purposes of Effects.

### J. The Hand (not pictured) {#j.-the-hand-(not-pictured)}

A pool of cards used during the game. Cards are drawn from the deck.

1. Cards in the Hand are not In Play.  
2. The contents of a Player’s Gand is private information.  
3. Players may not look at the contents of their Opponent’s Hand unless an Effect instructs them to do so.  
4. The number of cards in each player’s Hand is public information.   
5. The maximum number of cards a player can have in their Hand at the end of their turn is 7\.  
6. A player may change the order of cards in their Hand as often as they like at any point in the game.  
7. A player may consult the cards in their Hand at any moment, even in the middle of resolving Effects.  
8. If an effect of a card involves revealing itself to any player as part of its effect, it is only revealed until the effect resolves or the card moves to another area, whichever happens first.  
9. A card may be revealed multiple times in the same turn.  
10. After a card is revealed, when returned to the hand as private, it is considered a new copy of the card and may use any effects again.

    

### K. General Play Area (not pictured) {#k.-general-play-area-(not-pictured)}

When a Card is played, when placing it on the Chain it is placed face-up on the game board in any open space available where both players are able to clearly see (and pick up and read if they need to). Once the card resolves, it Moves to the game zone it’s intended to Move to.

1. Cards in the General Play Area are not In Play.

# 4\. Priority and Chains {#4.-priority-and-chains}

## 4.1. Priority {#4.1.-priority}

During each player’s turn, both players have the opportunity to play cards or use Effects. In addition, players have the opportunity to use cards or Effects in response to a card or Effect being used. Players do not do this simultaneously, instead going back and forth alternating in turns. “Priority” is used to define when it’s a player’s turn to use a card. The “Chain” is used to define how cards used in sequence apply their Effects and in what order.

### 4.1.1. Using Priority {#4.1.1.-using-priority}

When a player has Priority, they have the right to play a card, use an Effect or Charge cards from their Hand (when timing is appropriate, see Turn Flow section).

### 4.1.2. Gaining Priority {#4.1.2.-gaining-priority}

	Priority is gained in the following ways:

1. At the beginning of each phase of a turn, after performing all mandatory actions, the Turn player gains Priority.  
2. After resolving all parts of a Chain, the turn player gains Priority.  
3. After a player performs an action that is placed on a Chain, the opposing player gains Priority.  
4. If any player elects to do nothing rather than use Priority, they pass Priority to the next player. If all players pass Priority, rather than repeat this process, the game proceeds to either resolve the current Chain, or if there is no Chain to resolve, the next phase of the turn.

## 4.2. Chains {#4.2.-chains}

Whenever a card is played or an Effect is activated, the Effect is not immediately applied. Instead, the card or Effect is placed onto a “Chain” of Effects waiting to resolve. A “Chain” doesn’t refer to a specific location on the game board, but rather refers to a system of organization that is meant to help players sort out the order in which their cards apply their Effects. There can only be one Chain at a time.

When a player places a card or Effect onto the Chain, Priority is passed to the opposing player who then has the opportunity to place a card or Effect of their own. If they do, Priority goes back to the first player and this process repeats with alternating play.

If a player chooses to do nothing and passes Priority after their opponent plays a card or Effect, that opponent may either play an additional card or Effect by placing it onto the Chain, or they may also choose to do nothing and pass Priority. If they do play a card or Effect, this process starts back at the beginning, and the other player may once again decide to play a card/Effect or do nothing. If both players choose to pass Priority one after the other, no other cards/Effects may be played and the Chain resolves. 

![][image2]

After the Chain resolves, the turn player gains Priority again and this process repeats until both players have passed Priority and the game moves to the next phase.

### 4.2.1. What Starts/Adds to a Chain? {#4.2.1.-what-starts/adds-to-a-chain?}

Chains are started or added to by the following actions:  
Activate Effects  
Trigger Effects  
Summoning a Character Card (and Effects that Summon like Transformation)  
Playing a Strategy Card  
Playing an Ability Card

### 4.2.2. Resolving the Chain {#4.2.2.-resolving-the-chain}

Chains are resolved backwards, meaning the card most recently played will apply its Effect first, and the first card played will be the last to apply its Effect. Once a card or activated Effect finishes applying its Effect, it is “resolved” and the Chain Moves on to the next card or Effect waiting to resolve.

After every Effect on the Chain resolves, any trigger Effects that met their activation condition while the Chain was resolving may then activate in the order in which their conditions were met. If multiple trigger Effects meet their activation condition at the same time, all of the Turn Player’s are placed on the Chain first, followed by the Non-Turn Player.  
	When resolving an Effect that Targets, at least one of the Targets must still be a legal Target at the time of resolution, otherwise the entire effect fails and is not applied. If at least 1 of the declared Targets is still a Target at the time of resolution, the Effect will resolve and do as much as it can.

# 5\. Turn Flow and Breakdown {#5.-turn-flow-and-breakdown}

## 5.1. Setup {#5.1.-setup}

To prepare for a game of Primal, each player does the following in order:

1. Separate your Field card from your deck and place it face up in your Field Area.  
2. Shuffle your deck and place it face down in the Deck Area.  
3. Roll dice or flip a coin to determine which player goes first as the “Turn Player”.  
4. Set your Turn Marker to 0\.  
5. If a Field Card has a Trigger Effect that Activates at the start of the game (*e.g. 0001 Henratta)*, that Effect activates now, forming a Chain starting with the Turn Player if necessary.  
6. Draw a six card Hand to use at the start of the game.   
   1. If you don’t like any of the cards you drew in your first six cards, you may Move any number of them to the bottom of your deck, draw that many cards, then shuffle your deck. You may only do this once per game.

## 5.2. Start Phase {#5.2.-start-phase}

	The Start Phase is always performed in the following order:

1. Remove one Permanent Counter from all Permanent (X) Strategy cards in play controlled by the turn player. If the last Permanent Counter is removed from a card in this way, it is immediately Moved to the owner’s Essence area and any continuous Effects are no longer applied.  
   1. If multiple Permanent (X) Strategy cards would have Permanent Counters removed, the removal of Counters or (for Permanent (X) Strategy Cards with the last Counter removed) Movement to the essence area is simultaneous.  
   2. If a Trigger Effect would activate in response to the removal of a Counter or a card moving to the essence area (such as a permanent strategy removing its last Counter), it activates now.  
2. Any Effects that were applied earlier (or in a previous turn) that last until the start of the turn stop applying. Any actions instructed to be performed at the start of the turn by an Effect applied earlier (or in a previous turn) are performed now.  
3. If a Trigger Effect would activate due the turn player entering the start phase (cards with “At the start of your turn” or “At the start of your opponent’s turn for example), that Effect activates now.  
4. The Turn Player Draws 1 Card. This start of turn draw is also referred to as a “Normal Draw” by effects.  
   1. This step is skipped if it’s the player going first’s 1st turn of the game.  
   2. If a player is unable to draw a card due to having no cards in their deck, play continues to the Main Phase.  
5. Proceed to the Main Phase.

## 5.3. Main Phase {#5.3.-main-phase}

### 5.3.1. Start of Main Phase {#5.3.1.-start-of-main-phase}

At the beginning of the Main Phase, check for any Trigger Effects that indicate they activate due to the start of the main phase and activate them now.   
After completing this check and resolving the Chain (if any), the turn player gains Priority, and the actions either player may perform while they have Priority are listed in the following sections.

### 5.3.2. Main Phase as the Turn Player {#5.3.2.-main-phase-as-the-turn-player}

	During the Main Phase, the turn player may perform as many of these actions as they would like in any order while they have Priority:

1. Summon a Character Card (Once per turn)  
   1. If a character card in your Hand has a Turn Cost equal to or less than your current turn Marker, you may declare that you are Summoning that character and follow these steps in order:  
      1. Move the card into the general play area.  
         2. If the Character Card has a Hand Cost, place the number indicated into your essence area. Hand Costs must always be paid with cards with any matching Symbols as the card you want to play.  
         3. Place the Summon onto the Chain. It is *not* a card Effect. Priority is passed to the opponent and the Chain builds and resolves as normal.  
         4. Once the Chain resolves, Move the Character to your Kingdom in Healthy status in its own Team.  
   2. Summoning a Character may only be performed as the first action placed on the Chain.  
   3. When moving the card to your Kingdom, it is considered both a Summon and a Put in Play action for the purposes of other card Effects.  
   4. If a Character has Unique or Transformation (Which includes Unique in its Effect), you may not attempt to Summon that Character if a card with the same Print Number is already in play.  
   5. If an Effect would instruct a player to “Summon” a character, as it resolves, the Character is Put in Play and is considered to have been Summoned (a new Chain is not started for the Summon, and this method of potentially Summoning a Character as a second or later Effect on a Chain is considered an exception to Summoning rules).   
      1. Summoning in this way may only be performed if the player using the Effect has not already Summoned a character, and that player may not Summon a Character conventionally afterward.  
      2. Hand Cost and Turn Cost requirements must still be met.  
      3. A player may use an Effect to Summon a character in this way when it is not their own turn.

         

2. Play a Strategy Card (Once per turn)  
   1. If your Strategy Card in your Hand has a Turn Cost equal to or less than your current turn marker, you may play it by following these steps in order:  
      1. Move the card to your General Play Area  
         2. Declare the target of the Strategy if it has one  
            1. If the card indicates a target and there is no applicable target declare, the card cannot be played  
         3. Place any Hand Cost indicated by the Strategy card into the Essence Area  
         4. Place the Strategy Card onto the Chain. Priority is passed to the opponent and the Chain builds and resolves as normal.  
         5. When the Strategy Card resolves, apply its Effects, then Move it to your Essence Area.  
   2. Strategy Cards with the **Permanent** keyword Move to your Kingdom when they resolve instead of the Essence Area. It will remain in the Kingdom until the game ends or an Effect removes it, and it may apply any of its Effects provided it remains in play and any additional requirements it may have are met.   
      1. If the **Permanent** keyword includes a number in parenthesis “( )”, it enters the Kingdom with that many Permanent Counters on it. At the start of each of its controller’s turns, remove one Counter, and when the last one is removed, immediately stop applying its Effects and Move it to the owner’s Essence Area.  
   3. If a Strategy has the **Counter** keyword, you may not play it as the turn player.  
   4. Strategy Cards may either start a Chain or add to an existing Chain.  
   5. If a Strategy has Unique, you may not attempt to play that Strategy if a card with the same Print Number is already in play.

      

3. Use an Activate \[Main\] Effect (No limit per turn)  
   1. Follow these steps in order:  
      1. If the Effect refers to a Target, declare it  
         1. If the Effect requires a target and there is no applicable target declare, the Effect cannot be activated  
         2. Pay the Cost for the Effect  
            1. The Cost is any action instructed to perform written in bold before the “:” of the Effect’s text. It may also be indicated as Essence Symbols, in which case the Cost is to Move one card with a matching Symbol from the Essence Area to the Discard pile for each Symbol in the Cost area.  
            2. If the Cost indicates a Neutral Essence Symbol with a number on it, Move that number of cards with any Symbol from the essence area to the Discard pile. If a Neutral Essence Symbol indicates 0, no essence is Moved, but this is still considered a Cost. If a Neutral Symbol indicates X as a Cost, Move any number (including 0\) of cards of any Symbol from the essence area to the Discard pile.  
         3. Place the Effect onto the Chain. Priority is passed to the opponent and Chain building and resolution rules apply.  
            1. The card with the Effect being used is not Moved to the general play area and remains where it was when activated unless it Moved to a new area as part of its Cost.  
   2. Activate Effects may either start a Chain or add to an existing Chain.

4. Charge Essence (No limit per turn)  
   1. You may Move any number of cards from your Hand to your Essence Area.  
      1. You may only Charge Essence when there are no Effects on a Chain.  
      2. Charging Essence does not start a Chain or pass Priority.  
      3. Charging Essence this way may only be done using cards from your Hand. Charging Essence from other areas is exclusive to card effects.

   

5. Pass Priority  
   1. The turn player may elect to do nothing and pass Priority to their opponent.

### 5.3.3. Main Phase as the Non-Turn Player {#5.3.3.-main-phase-as-the-non-turn-player}

	During the Main Phase, the non-turn player may perform as many of these actions as they would like in any order while they have Priority (see the above section for each respective action’s specific instructions and properties):

1. Play a Strategy Card (Once per turn)  
   1. The Strategy Card must either have the **Counter** keyword or specify that it may be used during an opponent’s turn. Strategy Cards missing this requirement may not be used as the Non-Turn Player.  
2. Use an Activate \[Main\] Effects (No limit per turn)  
3. Pass Priority

### 5.3.4 Ending the Main Phase {#5.3.4-ending-the-main-phase}

The Main phase is ended after The Turn player passes Priority while there are no Effects being placed onto a Chain, followed by the Non-Turn player passing Priority back in sequence. The Turn Player may not unilaterally decide the Main Phase is over. They *must* pass Priority to the opponent, who may perform any action available to them if they choose to, in which case the Main Phase continues if that action was not passing Priority.

After the Turn Player and Non-Turn player pass Priority in sequence in this way, the Main Phase immediately ends. Neither Player may decide to continue with the Main Phase and any opportunity to perform any Main Phase action is forfeit as the game proceeds to the Organization phase.

## 5.4. Organization Phase {#5.4.-organization-phase}

During the Organization Phase, the turn player may arrange their Characters into stacks of up to 3 cards called Teams.  
   
At the beginning of the Organization phase, check for any Trigger Effects that indicate they activate due to the start of the Organization phase and activate them now. After completing this check and resolving the Chain (if any), the turn player performs the following steps in order: 

1. Separate all Characters in the Turn Player’s Kingdom into Teams of 1 Character each.  
2. Organize all Characters in the Turn Player’s Kingdom into as many Teams as they like, with a maximum of 3 characters per Team.   
3. Declare whether to proceed to the Battle Phase or End Phase, then proceed to that phase.   
   1. If it’s the player who went first’s 1st turn, they must proceed to the End Phase.  
   2. If play proceeds to the End phase, the Battle Phase is not entered, and players may not use any Effects that are applicable during the Battle Phase.

## 5.5. Battle Phase {#5.5.-battle-phase}

At the beginning of the Battle phase, check for any Trigger Effects that indicate they  activate due to the start of the Battle phase and activate them now. After completing this check and resolving the Chain (if any), both players will perform the following actions as directed in order:

### 5.5.1. Attack Step {#5.5.1.-attack-step}

The Turn Player selects up to three Teams they control and Moves them from their Kingdom to their Battlefield as Attacking Teams.

1. For each Team Moved to the Battlefield, a Team Lead is designated and Moved to the top of the stack of cards for that respective Team. The other characters (if any) are designated as Team Support. This designation lasts for the remainder of the Battle Phase.  
   1. If the Team Lead is removed from the Team for any reason, any remaining characters are still designated as Team Support and a new Team Lead is not designated.  
      2. A Team may not have more than 1 Team Lead. If an Effect is later applied that would cause a character in a Team to be designated as a Team Lead, when that happens, the previous Team Lead will then be designated as Team Support.  
   2. If the Turn Player selects no Teams to Move to the Battlefield, the rest of these steps are skipped and the turn proceeds directly to the End Phase   
   3. If an Effect would prevent a Character from being “Sent out to Battle” or “Sent out to Attack”, that character’s entire Team may not be Moved to the Battlefield.  
   4. All Teams sent out to battle/Attack are done so simultaneously.  
   5. This Movement is considered “Sending out to battle” as well as “Sending out to Attack.”  
   6. If an applicable Trigger Effect would activate in response to the turn player’s characters being “sent out to battle” or “sent out to Attack”, it activates now.   
      1. Trigger Effects with the activation condition of a being sent out to battle/Attack *and opposed* do not activate now.

### 5.5.2. Block Step {#5.5.2.-block-step}

The Non-Turn Player may select Teams they control and Move them from their Kingdom to their Battlefield as Blocking Teams, up to the number of Teams the Turn Player sent out to Attack.

1. For each Team Moved to the Battlefield, a Team Lead is designated and Moved to the top of the stack of cards for that respective Team. The other characters (if any) are designated as Team Support. This designation lasts for the remainder of the Battle Phase.  
   1. If the Team Lead is removed from the Team for any reason, any remaining characters are still designated as Team Support and a new Team Lead is not designated.  
   2. A Team may not have more than 1 Team Lead. If an Effect is later applied that would cause a character in a Team to be designated as a Team Lead, when that happens, the previous Team Lead will then be designated as Team Support.  
2. The Non-Turn player may elect not to Block at all, in which case the rest of this step is skipped and the game Moves directly to the Exchange of Ability step of the Battle Phase.  
3. If an Effect would prevent a Character from being “Sent out to Battle” or “Sent out to Block”, that character’s entire Team may not be Moved to the Battlefield.  
4. All Teams sent out to battle/Block are done so simultaneously.  
5. The Non-Turn player assigns each Blocking Team to different Attacking Teams until all Blocking Teams have been assigned, positioning them to be directly across from the Team they are Blocking as a visual indicator.  
   1. An Attacking Team may only be Blocked by exactly one Team.  
      2. A Blocking Team may only Block exactly one Team.  
6. An Attacking Team being Blocked is “opposed” and the characters in the Blocking Team are “opposing” the Attacking characters. A Blocking Team Blocking an Attacking Team is “opposed” and the characters in the Attacking Team are “opposing” the Blocking characters.  
   7. This Movement is considered “Sending out to battle” as well as “Sending out to Block”. Additionally, if a Team Blocks or is Blocked, it is also considered “sending out to Attack and opposed” or “sent out to Block and opposed” for Attackers and Blockers respectively, as well as “sent out to battle and opposed” for either player’s cards.  
   8. If an applicable Trigger Effect would activate in response to either player’s character being “sent out to Block”, “sent out to Block and opposed”, “sent out to Attack and opposed”, “sent out to battle and opposed”, or the Non-Turn player’s character being “Sent out to battle” it activates now. 

#### 5.2.2.1. Stand-by Characters {#5.2.2.1.-stand-by-characters}

Any characters either Player controls that were not Moved to the Battlefield and remain in the Kingdom are considered Stand-by.

1. If a character on the battlefield is made Stand-by by an Effect, it is Moved to the controller’s Kingdom in its own Team and is no longer sent to battle, Attacking, Blocking, opposing, or opposed.  
2. If multiple characters in the same Team are made Stand-by simultaneously, they are Moved to the controller’s Kingdom in a Team together.  
3. Stand-by Characters may not be the Users of ability cards, but may activate their Effects.  
4. Stand-by Characters may not be made Stand-by by effects.

### 5.5.3. Exchange of Ability Step {#5.5.3.-exchange-of-ability-step}

At the beginning of the Exchange of Ability (EOA), check for any Trigger Effects that indicate they activate due to the start of the EOA and activate them now. After completing this check and resolving the Chain (if any), the turn player gains Priority.   
During the EOA step, either player may perform the following actions while they have Priority:

1. Play an Ability Card  
   1. To play an Ability Card, follow these these steps in order:  
      1. Move the card from your Hand to the General Play Area  
      2. Declare the User of the Ability Card  
         1. The User must be a character in the Battlefield Area. If an ability card specifies requirements that can’t be met, the card cannot be played.  
      3. Declare the Target of the Ability Card, if any  
         1. If the card indicates a target and there is no applicable target to declare, the card cannot be played.  
      4. Pay the Cost of the Ability Card  
         1. Move one card with a matching Symbol from the Essence Area to the Discard pile for each Symbol in the Cost area.  
            2. If the Cost indicates a Neutral Essence Symbol with a number on it, Move that number of cards with any Symbol from the essence area to the Discard pile. If a Neutral Essence Symbol indicates 0, no essence is Moved, but this is still considered a Cost. If a Neutral Symbol indicates X as a Cost, Move any number (including 0\) of cards of any Symbol from the essence area to the Discard pile  
      5. Place the Ability card on to the Chain. Priority is passed to the opponent and normal Chain building and resolution rules apply.  
      6. When the Ability Card resolves, apply its Effects and Move it to your essence area 

      

2. Use an Activate Effect with \[EOA\] timing  
   1. See “Use an Activate \[Main\] Effect” during the Main Phase for instruction on use of Activate Effects.  
3. Pass Priority

If either player plays an Ability Card or uses an Activate Effect with \[EOA\] timing, normal Chain/Priority rules apply. After the Chain resolves, the Turn Player gains Priority, and this process may repeat. There is no limit to the amount of Chains that may occur during EOA.

If due a card or Effect all characters in a Team are removed from the Battlefield, the characters in that Team are no longer Attacking, Blocking or opposed, and the remaining Team is also no longer opposed.

#### 5.5.3.1. Ending the Exchange of Ability Step {#5.5.3.1.-ending-the-exchange-of-ability-step}

The EOA step is ended after the Turn player passes Priority while there are no Effects being placed onto a Chain, followed by the Non-Turn player passing Priority back in sequence. The Turn Player may not unilaterally decide the EOA step is over. They *must* pass Priority to the opponent, who may perform any action available to them if they choose to, in which case the EOA step continues if that action was not passing Priority.

After the Turn Player and Non-Turn player pass Priority in sequence in this way, the EOA step immediately ends. Neither Player may decide to continue with the EOA step and any opportunity to perform any EOA action is forfeit as the game proceeds to the Showdown step.

### 5.5.4. Showdown Step {#5.5.4.-showdown-step}

At the start of the showdown step, check for any Trigger Effects that indicate they activate due to the start of the Showdown and activate them now. Any lingering Effects previously put into Effect that would be applied during the showdown (e.g. *0038 Swift Strike*) are also applied now.

After completing this check and resolving the Chain (if any), resolve the showdown for each Team sent out to Attack, one at a time. The Turn Player decides which Showdown to perform. 

To resolve the of showdown, perform the following:

1. Calculate the Team Power of each participating Team  
   1. Add the Lead value of the Team Lead (if any) to the Support Value of the Team Support (if any).  
      1. If a character is no longer in its Team or in play during the showdown, it does not contribute its Lead or Support values to the Team Power, but characters remaining in the Team still do.  
      2. If all of the Attacking characters in a Team are no longer on the Battlefield, the Showdown does not occur for that Team (or the Blocking Team) and no outcome is determined, in which case the next unresolved Attacking Team should begin resolution of the showdown. If there are no showdowns left to resolve, proceed directly to step 7\.  
2. If the Attacking Team is Blocked, compare the Team Power of both the Attacking and Blocking Teams.  
3. Determine the result based on the following:

   3.1. If the Attack is not (or no longer) Blocked and

   1. The Attacking Team’s Team Power is 4 or less:  
      The result of the Attack is a Battle Reward \- The Attacking player wins 1 Battle Reward, and the top card of their opponent’s deck is Moved face down to the Battle Reward Area.  
   2. The Attacking Team’s Team Power is 5 or greater:  
      The result of the Attack is an Outstanding Battle Reward \- The Attacking player wins 2 Battle Rewards, and the top 2 cards of their opponent’s deck is Moved face down to the Battle Reward Area.  
      

   3.2. If the Attack is Blocked and  
1. The difference in Team Power between the Attacking and Blocking Teams is 4 or less:  
   1. The result of the battle is a Victory, awarded to the Team with the higher Team Power.   
   2. 1 Damage is dealt to the Team Lead of the Team with the lower Team Power.  
      1. If any Team Leader on the Team with lower Team Power is no longer on the battlefield, no Damage is dealt.

         

2. The difference in Team Power between the Attacking and Blocking Teams is 5 or greater:  
   1. The result of the battle is an Outstanding Victory, awarded to the Team with the higher Team Power.   
   2. 2 Damage is dealt to the Team Lead and 1 Damage is dealt to each Team Support of the Team with the lower Team Power.  
      1. If any Team Leader or Support on the Team with lower Team Power is no longer on the battlefield, no Damage is dealt to that respective character (any remaining characters still take Damage).  
3. Both the Attacking and Blocking Teams have the same Team Power:  
   1. The result of the battle is a Stalemate and both Team Leads are dealt 1 Damage.  
      1. If any Team Leader on either Team is no longer on the battlefield, no Damage is dealt to the Team(s) with no Team Leader.

4\. Apply the determined result, dealing Damage or awarding Battle Rewards.

1. Any Effect that would increase, decrease, replace, or otherwise modify any result of the showdown is applied at this time (e.g. *0074 Spike the Impaler*).

5\. If a trigger Effect would activate due to one of these results of the showdown, it activates now. Examples of potential triggers include:

1. A Team being awarded a Victory, Outstanding Victory, stalemate, Battle Reward or Outstanding Battle Reward  
2. Dealing or receiving Damage as a result of the Showdown  
3. Causing or incurring injuries from Damage as a result of the Showdown  
4. Character cards being Discarded due to Showdown Damage

6\. If any Attacking Teams have not resolved the Showdown, the Turn Player selects the next Showdown to resolve and returns to step 1\. If all Attacking Teams have resolved the Showdown, proceed to step 7\.

7\. All characters remaining on the battlefield are returned to their respective controller’s Kingdoms and the game proceeds to the End Phase.

## 5.6. End Phase {#5.6.-end-phase}

The End Phase is the final phase where players check for a winner and prepare for the next player’s turn. The End Phase is always performed in the following order:

1. Check for Battle Rewards  
   1. If just one player has 10 or more Battle Rewards, that player wins the game. If both players have 10 or more Battle Rewards, the Turn Player wins.  
2. Check for remaining Cards in Deck  
   1. If just one player has no cards remaining in their Deck, that player loses the game (and the other wins). If both players have no cards remaining in their Deck, the Turn Player loses. Losing as a result of having cards remaining in a player’s deck is referred to as a “Deck Out”.  
      1. If an effect would prevent 1 or more players from losing to Deck Out, *e.g. 0239 Cerulean Nanami,* this loss is ignored for the affected players and play continues to the next step.  
3. Any actions instructed to be performed at the end of the turn by an Effect applied earlier in the turn are performed now. Any Effects that were activated earlier that last until the end of the turn stop applying.   
   1. Effects that were activated earlier that last until the end of the turn that would give a card a Trigger effect that activates at the end of the turn (*e.g. 0115 Vispa)* don’t stop applying until after the next step.  
4. If a Trigger Effect would activate due the turn player entering the end phase, that Effect activates now.  
   1. Effects that were activated earlier that last until the end of the turn that would give a card a Trigger effect that activates at the end of the turn (*e.g. 0115 Vispa)* stop applying after this Chain resolves.  
5. If the turn player’s Hand size exceeds the 7 card maximum, they Discard cards until they have 7\.  
6. The turn player Moves their Turn Marker up.

Once these steps are completed, the next player takes their turn and begins their Start Phase. The game will continue to repeat this process until a player wins.

## 5.7. Trigger Effects that Activate in Response to Game Procession {#5.7.-trigger-effects-that-activate-in-response-to-game-procession}

Throughout the course of a turn there are multiple timing windows for trigger Effects that would activate in response to a change of gamestate caused by procession of game flow.   
Examples include:  
	Beginning of a phase or step of a phase.  
	Movement of a card or game piece due to procession of a turn.

These timing windows occur only once, and all Trigger Effects that would activate in response to these timings are placed onto a single Chain. Once that Chain resolves, any new Effects that would be activated in response to the original timing window may not activate (a trigger Effect that would be activated due to an action performed by an Effect resolving in that Chain may still be activated).

1. All of the turn player’s trigger Effects are placed on this Chain before the non-turn player’s trigger Effects.  
2. Each player may place their respective trigger Effects onto the Chain in the order of their choosing, regardless of whether the Effect is optional or mandatory. However, if a mandatory trigger Effect has not been placed on the Chain and the player has already placed all optional trigger Effects available to them, they *must* place their mandatory trigger Effects on the Chain before the game can proceed. Additionally, each player must declare if they are not activating any optional triggers when addressing all trigger Effects that would be activated and may not activate them later in the Chain if they choose not to activate them.  
3. After all trigger Effects are placed on the Chain, normal Chain and Priority rules apply. Players may add to this Chain as appropriate.

# 6\. Card Properties {#6.-card-properties}

## 6.1. General Properties {#6.1.-general-properties}

### 6.1.1. Symbols {#6.1.1.-symbols}

All cards feature at least one Symbol in the upper right Hand corner. If a card has multiple Symbols, it is considered to have each of those Symbols at all times. 

If an Effect refers to or targets a card(s) with any 1 specific Symbol and a card with multiple Symbols has the Symbol specified, that Card may be affected or targeted by the Effect.

Cards with multiple Symbols may not be treated as multiple cards for the purpose of paying Essence Costs.

Necro, Water, Terra, Fire, Air and Plasma Symbols may be referred to as “specific” Symbols when identifying Symbols paid as Costs to differentiate them from Neutral Essence.

### 6.1.2. Costs {#6.1.2.-costs}

	In order to activate an Effect or play a card, Costs must be paid. Universal Rule 1.3. does not apply to being unable to pay Costs.

#### 6.1.2.1. Turn Cost {#6.1.2.1.-turn-cost}

All Character and Strategy Cards feature a Turn Cost represented by a number overlaid on an image of a 10-sided die.![][image3]  
In order to Play any Strategy Card or Summon any Character Card, the Player attempting that action’s Turn Marker must be equal to or greater than the Turn Cost of that card.  
In order to put a Character Card In Play using the Transformation Effect, the Player attempting that action’s Turn Marker must be equal to or greater than 1 less than the Turn Cost of that card.

When putting a Character Card in play through any other means, Turn Cost is ignored unless otherwise specified.

Turn Costs may be increased or decreased by Effects, but may not be reduced below 0\.

#### 6.1.2.2. Hand Cost {#6.1.2.2.-hand-cost}

All Character and Strategy Cards feature a Hand Cost represented by a number overlaid on an image of two Primal TCG cards. ![][image4]

In order to Play any Strategy Card or Summon any Character Card, the Player attempting that action must Move cards of a matching Symbol from their Hand to the Essence Area equal to the number indicated by the Hand Cost.

When putting a Character Card in play through any other means, Hand Cost is ignored unless otherwise specified.

Hand Costs may be increased or decreased by Effects, but may not be reduced below 0\.

When moving multiple cards to the Essence Area for Hand Cost, those cards are Moved simultaneously. 

#### 6.1.2.3. Essence Cost {#6.1.2.3.-essence-cost}

Ability Cards and Effects found on cards may indicate their Cost as individual Symbols. One card of a matching Symbol must be Moved from the Essence Area to the Discard Pile for each Symbol in the Cost.  
Neutral Essence is represented by its own Symbol ![][image5] overlaid with a number, indicating the number of cards of any Symbol to Move to pay the Cost.

If a Neutral Essence indicates 0 Essence, no cards need to be Moved to fulfill the Cost.

If a Neutral Essence indicates X Essence, the controller of the Effect may Move any number of cards to fulfill the Cost, including 0\. If an Effect indicates X essence and refers to X targets, the controller of the Effect may not pay an amount that would exceed the number of legal targets. All cards paid for X are paid simultaneously.

After X Essence is paid for an Ability Card or Effect, the X Essence Symbol is now considered to be a Neutral Essence with a number equal to the amount paid for the X.  
 *Example: A player plays 0036 Stake Gun and pays 1 Necro and 3 additional Essence for the X. Until the Chain has fully resolved, Stake Gun’s Essence Cost is considered 1 Necro and 3 Neutral Essence.*

### 6.1.3. Attached Cards and Cards Placed Underneath Cards {#6.1.3.-attached-cards-and-cards-placed-underneath-cards}

Attached cards are placed face-up underneath an In Play card with one stacked on the other. 

Attached cards are not considered in play, even if the card they are Attached to is. Attaching a card from any area to an In Play card is not putting the Attached card In Play.

Attached cards don’t do anything by themselves unless specified by their card text and are Moved to the Discard pile when the card they are Attached is Moved to a non-In Play area or otherwise leaves play.

Any number of cards may be Attached to a single card.

When an In-Play card is Attached to another card, it is considered to have left play and any Effects (including the Attached card’s) that would activate due to a card leaving play may be activated.

If a card specifically places a card underneath another card (such as with S0095 Synthetic Research) without using the word “Attach”, that card is not considered Attached to the card and isn’t able to be interacted with by effects that affect Attached cards. Cards that are underneath other cards otherwise function like Attached cards with this exception. Attached cards may also be interacted with by Effects that refer to cards underneath cards but do not use “Attached” specifically.

### 6.1.3.1. Detaching Cards {#6.1.3.1.-detaching-cards}

	Detaching a card refers to moving an Attached card to the owner’s Discard Pile. Cards placed underneath other cards without using the word “Attach” (such as with S0095 Synthetic Research) may not be Detached.

### 6.1.4. New Instances of the Same Card {#6.1.4.-new-instances-of-the-same-card}

With the exception of Movement between the Kingdom and Battlefield areas, whenever a card Moves to a different area, that card is considered a new instance of itself and any Effects previously applied to the card are no longer applied.

*Example: An Effect is applied to an In Play Character Negates that Character’s Effect until the end of the turn. Later that same turn, that Character Card is Moved to the Discard Pile and then Put in Play again. The Character Card is considered a new instance of card, and its Effect text is not Negated. The same could be applied to cases where Cards have Effects that may only be applied once per turn.*

When an effect refers to “other” cards or “another” card, it refers to other physical game pieces. If an effect that refers to “other” cards or “another” card moves to a different game zone, treating it as a new copy of the card, it may still not select itself as a target.

## 6.2. Character Card Properties {#6.2.-character-card-properties}

This section details properties specific to Character Cards.

### 6.2.1. Playing a Character Card {#6.2.1.-playing-a-character-card}

Character cards may be Summoned once per turn during the turn player’s main phase when there are no other Effects on a Chain and the player has Priority. Summoning is broken down into the following steps:

1. Place the Character card face-up into the General Play Area.  
2. Pay the Character Card’s Hand Cost (if any) to your essence area.  
   1. If you cannot pay the Hand Cost, you may not attempt to Summon the Character.  
3. Place the Summon on the Chain.   
   1. The character is still in the General Play Area at this time and may not be targeted by Effects referring to in play or controlled cards.  
4. Resolve the Chain, placing the character card onto your Kingdom zone in its own Team.  
   

Entrance Cost requirements must be met in order to Summon a Character card. If the player’s turn marker does not meet or exceed the printed Turn Cost they may not attempt to Summon the card.

Summoning is considered to be putting a character in play, but putting a character in play is *not* considered to be Summoning.

If an Effect would put a character in play, Hand Cost and Turn Cost do not need to be adhered to unless specifically stated by the Effect.

There is no limit to the number of character cards that may be put in play in a turn.

### 6.2.2. Stat Values {#6.2.2.-stat-values}

Stat Values refer to Character’s Lead and Support values and are represented by the Lead Value separated from the Support Value with a forward slash “/”. A Character with 2 Lead and 0 Support would have its Stat Values written as “2/0”.

Stat Values have no upper or lower limits and may go into the negatives. A character is not Discarded if its Stat Values go below 0\.

### 6.2.3. Healthy and Injured States {#6.2.3.-healthy-and-injured-states}

Characters have two states, Healthy and Injured. 

Healthy refers to a Character in the upright and vertical position. It uses the Stat Values on the lower right Hand corner of the card.

Injured refers to a Character in the rotated and horizontal position. It uses the Stat Values on the lower left Hand corner of the card when positioned in this way. 

When an Effect Injures a character, the Character is changed to the Injured state. This is not considered Damage. If an Effect attempts to Injure an already Injured character, nothing happens.

When an Effect Heals a character, the character is changed to the Healthy state. If an Effect attempts to Heal an already Healthy character, nothing happens.

#### 6.2.3.1 Injured Character Effects {#6.2.3.1-injured-character-effects}

When a Character is Injured, its Effects may not be activated or applied unless it begins with “Valid”.

Any Effects from a Character placed on a Chain before the Character was Injured will do nothing when resolving if the Effect is not “Valid”.

If a Character has multiple Effects, each one must have “Valid” in order to be used while the Character is Injured.

If an Injured character has a Trigger Effect that is not “Valid” with an activation requirement that was met while the Effect was Injured, the Effect may not be activated even if Character would no longer be considered Injured when the Effect would be placed on the Chain, as the text describing the activation condition was not able to used.

If a Character with a once per turn/game Effect that does not have “Valid” activates its Effect and becomes Injured before its Effect resolves, The Effect is still considered to have been used for the purposes of activation limits. If the Character is no longer Injured afterward, the Effect is still considered the same one that was used and may not be used again.

### 6.2.4. Damage {#6.2.4.-damage}

When Damage is distributed to a character, the character’s state will change from Healthy to Injured, or it may be Discarded.

When a Healthy Character receives 1 Damage, the character is changed to Injured. This is also considered an Injury.

When a Healthy Character receives 2 or more Damage, the character is Discarded while in the Healthy state. The character is not Injured.

When an Injured Character receives 1 or more Damage, the character is Discarded while in the Injured state.

When a Character receives Damage reduced to or below 0, no Damage is dealt, and any Effects that depend on a Character receiving Damage in order to activate may not be used.

### 6.2.5. Characteristics and Attributes {#6.2.5.-characteristics-and-attributes}

Characteristics are always referred to by Effect texts in brackets “{ }”.  
Attributes are always referred to by Effect texts in angle brackets “\< \>”.

#### 6.2.5.1. “Name:” Characteristics {#6.2.5.1.-“name:”-characteristics}

Character cards with “Name:” are considered to have the name following the colon “:” in all areas in addition to their printed name.

#### 6.2.5.2 Token Characteristic {#6.2.5.2-token-characteristic}

Character cards with this Characteristic may not be included in a constructed deck and instead are Put in Play from outside of the game. When they leave play, they are removed from the game. See [2.2.1. Tokens](#2.2.1.-tokens).

If a card with {Token} would enter play but has a Hand Cost, the Hand Cost must be paid as the card enters play, even if the card is Put in Play using an effect.  
Players may elect not to pay the Hand Cost for cards with {Token}. If the Hand Cost isn't paid, the part of the effect that would Put in Play the Character with {Token} does nothing instead.

### 6.2.6. \+1/+1 Counters and \-1/-1 Counters  {#6.2.6.-+1/+1-counters-and--1/-1-counters}

\+1/+1 Counters and \-1/-1 Counters affect the Lead/Support values of the Characters they are placed on, increasing or decreasing those values respectively.

## 6.3. Strategy Card Properties {#6.3.-strategy-card-properties}

### 6.3.1. Playing a Strategy Card {#6.3.1.-playing-a-strategy-card}

During the main phase, each player may play one strategy card for the turn when they have Priority. The non-Turn Player may only play strategy cards with “**Counter**”.  
Strategy cards may be Chained to the Summon of a character card, the activation of an Effect, or the play of another strategy card.  
	Playing a strategy card is broken down into the following steps:

1. Place the Strategy card face-up into the General Play Area  
2. If the Strategy card refers to a target of its Effect, declare the target.  
   1. If the Strategy Card requires a target, but there isn’t one available, *the card cannot be activated.*  
3. Pay the Strategy Card’s Hand Cost (if any) to your essence area.  
   1. If you cannot pay the Hand Cost, you may not attempt to play the Strategy Card.  
4. Place the Strategy card on to the Chain.  
5. When the strategy card resolves, perform the Effect of the card, then Move the strategy card to your essence area. 

### 6.2.2. Permanent Strategy Cards {#6.2.2.-permanent-strategy-cards}

If the Strategy includes **Permanent**, instead of moving the Strategy card to your essence area, Move the Strategy card to your Kingdom. It will remain in play for the remainder of the game unless another Effect removes it. 

### 6.3.3. Permanent (x) Strategy Cards {#6.3.3.-permanent-(x)-strategy-cards}

If the Strategy includes **Permanent(x),** instead of moving the Strategy card to your essence area, Move the Strategy card to your Kingdom with a number of Permanent Counters on it equal to the number written on the **Permanent( )** keyword. At the start of each of the controller’s turns, remove one Counter from the game. When the final Counter is removed, any Effects applied by strategy are no longer in place and the card is Moved to the owner’s essence area.

	The Strategy Card enters play with the Permanent Counters already on it. The Counters are not placed on it after it enters play.

### 6.3.4. Counter Strategy Cards {#6.3.4.-counter-strategy-cards}

	Strategy cards with **Counter** may be played during an opponent’s turn only. They may not be played as the Turn Player.

## 6.4. Ability Card Properties {#6.4.-ability-card-properties}

### 6.4.1. Playing an Ability Card {#6.4.1.-playing-an-ability-card}

To play an Ability Card, follow these these steps in order:

1. Move the card from your Hand to the General Play Area  
2. Declare the User of the Ability Card  
   1. The User must be a character in the Battlefield Area. If an ability card specifies requirements that can’t be met, the card cannot be played.  
3. Declare the Target of the Ability Card, if any  
   1. If the card indicates a target and there is no applicable target to declare, the card cannot be played.  
4. Pay the Cost of the Ability Card  
   1. Move one card with a matching Symbol from the Essence Area to the Discard pile for each Symbol in the Cost area.  
   2. If the Cost indicates a Neutral Essence Symbol with a number on it, Move that number of cards with any Symbol from the essence area to the Discard pile. If a Neutral Essence Symbol indicates 0, no essence is Moved, but this is still considered a Cost. If a Neutral Symbol indicates X as a Cost, Move any number (including 0\) of cards of any Symbol from the essence area to the Discard pile  
5. Place the Ability card on to the Chain. Priority is passed to the opponent and normal Chain building and resolution rules apply.  
6. When the Ability Card resolves, apply its Effects and Move it to your essence area .

### 6.4.2. Ability Card Users {#6.4.2.-ability-card-users}

Ability Cards require a Character card to be used. If the declared User of the Ability Card is no longer on the Battlefield under the same player’s control when the Ability Card resolves, or if it no longer meets the prerequisites to be the User of the Ability Card, that card will do nothing when resolving instead of applying its Effect.

### 6.4.3. Requirements {#6.4.3.-requirements}

Ability Cards with Requirements cannot be used unless the User has the indicated trait. Requirements may include Names, Hand Costs, Turn Costs, Characteristics, Attributes, specified Stat Values or Symbols in any combination.

When resolving an Ability card with a Requirement, if the User no longer meets the Requirements, it is not a legal User of the Ability card and the Ability card will do nothing instead of applying its Effect.

### 6.4.4. Expert Effects {#6.4.4.-expert-effects}

Expert Effects are additional Effects that are applied when used by specific Character cards. Expert User requirements are indicated by brackets \[ \]. When resolving an Ability card that has its Expert requirement met, apply the Effects in the order printed. An Expert Effect may replace a part or whole Effect of the ability card’s original text.

Expert effects are not optional and must be applied if the User meets the Expert requirement. 

## 6.5. Field Card Properties {#6.5.-field-card-properties}

### 6.5.1. Unable to Move {#6.5.1.-unable-to-move}

Field cards may not be Moved from one area to another by another card’s Effects. If an Effect targeting a field card would Discard, Expel, Attach, or otherwise direct it to Move to another area, that part of the Effect does nothing.

### 6.5.2. Empty Field Area {#6.5.2.-empty-field-area}

If a player elects not to use a Field card, or if through the course of the game a Field card is no longer in a Field area, that player's Field area is considered to be "empty" and any effects with Field card specific requirements may not be used.

*Example: "Synthetic Laboratory" flips over, moves to the Kingdom, and becomes "Xeno". Until "Xeno" flips back over to "Synthetic Laboratory", the owner of “Xeno” is considered to have no Field card and may not place cards underneath their Field card even though "Synthetic Laboratory" is physically on the same card as “Xeno”.*

# 7\. Effect Texts {#7.-effect-texts}

## 7.1. Keywords {#7.1.-keywords}

Keywords are representative of text that appears on multiple cards. A card with a keyword is considered to have the Effect text or additional properties written on the card.

### 7.1.1. Transformation  {#7.1.1.-transformation}

Cards with Transformation have the following Effect texts:

* “During your Main Phase, if your Turn Marker is greater than or equal to this card's Turn Cost \-1, there are no cards or Effects on a chain, and you control a card that meets this card's Transformation requirement, you may pay this card's Hand Cost \-1 and add it to the chain with the following effect: Attach a card you control that meets this card's Transformation requirement to this card, and if you do, put this card in play. This is treated as a Summon and does not count toward the "one Summon per turn" limit."  
* “This card gains the Effect texts of any Character cards it Attached to perform Transformation.”  
* “This card gains Unique in all areas.”


  
Character cards with Transformation designate a specific trait of a character card in the Transformation requirements indicated by parenthesis “()”. If a character that meets the requirement is in play, and there are no Effects on a Chain, the Character card with Transformation may be Put in Play by Attaching that specified card to it. In addition to a put in play, this is also treated as a Summon, but does not count toward the once per turn Summon limit, and the Hand Cost and Turn Cost are each reduced by 1\. 

For example, a character with a Turn Cost of 6 and a Hand Cost of 2 could be put in play using Transformation when the owner’s turn marker is 5, and the player would only need to pay 1 Hand Cost. Afterward, any effects that might activate due to a character being either put in play or Summoned will activate.

To use Transformation, perform the following:

1. Place the Character card with Transformation face-up in the General Play Area.  
2. Pay the reduced Hand Cost (if any) to the Essence area.  
3. Place the effect on the Chain.  
   1.  While Transformation is an Effect that is added to the chain, it is not an Activate, Trigger, or Ongoing effect. Cards like *c0065 Raikiri* may not negate Transformation, but cards like *PR-0004 Little Devil* can.  
4. When Transformation resolves, remove the Character referred to by the Transformation keyword from play and Attach it to the Character card with Transformation, then put the Character card in play to the Kingdom in a Team by itself.

When a Character card is Put in Play/Summoned with Transformation, it gains the Effect text (and only the Effect text) of the Character card Attached to it to perform the Summon.

Character cards with Transformation are considered to be Unique in all areas.

Transformation is considered Effect text, so if the Effect of a card with Transformation is Negated, all of the above Effects are unable to be applied. Later, if Transformation is no longer negated, any effects that earlier met their condition to be applied (such as gaining the effect text of any Attached cards) will be applied again.

If a Character with Transformation has its Effect Negated, any Attached cards remain Attached.

If an Effect would allow a Character to be legally Put in Play using Transformation by Attaching a Character other than the named card in the requirements, the Character with Transformation still gains the Effect text of the Attached card, even if it isn’t the specified requirement..

If a card Effect would put in play a Character with Transformation and Attach a card to it, unless the action of putting the character in play is explicitly stated to be using Transformation, the Character with Transformation does not gain the Effect text of the Attached card, even if the Attached card is a card that meets the Transformation requirements.

If a Transformation effect fails to resolve due to negation or a change to the game state that would prevent it, the card with Transformation will return to whatever game zone it was in before Transformation was placed on the chain.

### 7.1.2. Camouflage  {#7.1.2.-camouflage}

Cards with Camouflage have the following Effect text:  
“This card may be Summoned from the Essence Area as though it were in your Hand.”

When using Camouflage, all other requirements of Summoning must still be met, and the mechanics of Summoning are otherwise identical. This effect may not be used in combination with other effects, such as Transformation.

Camouflage is considered Effect text, so it may be Negated, in which case the Character may not be Summoned from the Essence area.

### 7.1.3. Unique {#7.1.3.-unique}

Cards with Unique have the following Effect text:  
 	“Valid: This card may not enter or remain in play under a player’s control if that player already controls a card with the same print number.”

1. Players may not put Cards with Unique into play from any area if a card with the same print number is already under that player’s control, and Players may not attempt to perform an action (Summon, play the card, Transformation, etc.) that would put that card with Unique into play.  
2. Cards with Unique are not legal targets for Effects that would result in putting that card into play under a player’s control if that player already controls a card with the same print number.   
3. Effects that do not target may allow a Player to attempt to put in play a card with Unique.  
4. If an Effect would put in play a card with Unique into play under a Player’s control, but that player already controls a card with the same print number before the Effect resolves, that part of the Effect will do nothing and the card with Unique will remain where it was.   
5. If a card in the General Play Area would be put in play under player’s control (from Summoning, playing the card, Transformation, etc.), but a card with the same print number is put in play under the same player’s control before the first card can be put in play, the card in the General Play Area is Moved to the Discard Pile instead of the Kingdom.  
6. If a card would put in play multiple cards at the same time under the player’s control, and no cards with the same print number are in play, multiple copies of the same card with Unique are legal targets.  
7. If an Effect would put multiple copies of the same card with Unique into play at the same time, the controller of the Effect Moves only 1 from among the Unique cards into play and the rest remain where they were. Other targets of the Effect (if any) are still put in play.  
8. If multiple cards with the same print number are in play and gain Unique, the controller of those cards immediately selects one copy to remain in play and the rest are Moved to the Discard pile, even in the middle of the resolution of a Chain.

### 7.1.4. Counter {#7.1.4.-counter}

Cards with Counter have the following additional property (this is not an Effect text and cannot be interacted with by card Effects):  
“This card may be played during your opponent’s turn. This card cannot be played during your turn.”

Strategy Cards with Counter still need to meet all of the other requirements to be played. They still may only be played during the Main Phase.

### 7.1.5. Permanent {#7.1.5.-permanent}

Cards with Permanent have the following additional property (this is not an Effect text and cannot be interacted with by card Effects):  
When a card with Permanent would Move to the Essence Area after being played, it Moves to the Kingdom instead.

Cards with Permanent (X) have the following additional properties (this is not an Effect text and cannot be Negated or modified with by card Effects):  
When a card with Permanent (X)  would Move to the Essence Area after being played, it Moves to the Kingdom instead with X Permanent Counters.   
At the start of your turn, remove 1 Permanent Counter. When the last Permanent Counter is removed, cards with Permanent (X) are Moved to the Essence Area.

### 7.1.6. Expert {#7.1.6.-expert}

Ability Cards with Expert have the following additional property (this is not an Effect text and cannot be interacted with by card Effects):

When the User meets the requirements designated by the brackets “\[ \]” following the Expert Keyword of the Ability card, the additional Effect Text in the Expert line of the card may be applied.  
When resolving an Effect using Expert apply the Effects of the whole card in the order printed. An Expert Effect may replace a part or whole Effect of the ability card’s original text, in which case it will indicate if it does. 

While the Expert property can’t be Negated or changed, the Effect text that would be granted by meeting the Expert requirements can be. If an Ability card with Expert is Negated, all of the Effect text is Negated, including the Expert text.

### 7.1.7. Rebirth {#7.1.7.-rebirth}

Cards with Rebirth have the following Effect texts:

* “![][image6] Valid: This card is Summoned with a Rebirth Counter on it."  
* "![][image7] Valid: If this in-play Character is Discarded while it has a Rebirth Counter, put it in play from your Discard Pile. If this in-play Character would be Discarded while it has no Rebirth Counter, it is Expelled instead.”

Rebirth does not use the Chain. If a Character card with a Rebirth Counter on it is Discarded, it is put in play without starting a Chain as soon as there is no Chain resolving.

The effect to Put in Play the Character Discarded with a Rebirth Counter is mandatory.

### 7.1.8. Promote {#7.1.8.-promote}

Cards with Promote have the following Effect text:  
“![][image8]\[Your turn | Main\] **Pay this in-play card’s Promote cost, reveal a Character card from your hand that meets this card’s Promote requirement and has a Turn Cost equal to or less than this card’s Promote Value**: Put in play the revealed card, and if you do, move this card to the owner’s hand. This effect may not be used the turn this card is put in play.”

### 7.1.9. Rush {#7.1.9.-rush}

Cards with Rush have the following Effect text:  
“![][image8]\[EOA\] **Discard 1 Character card from your hand with the same Symbol and Attribute as this in-play card**: Apply this character’s Rush effect.”

	Upon resolving a Rush effect, the entirety of the effect written within parenthesis ( ) is resolved.  
	All Rush effects are initially ![][image8]effects, but a Rush effect may allow for a card to gain another type of effect. If it does, this is a lingering effect that lasts for a duration defined by the effect.  
Each player may only use Rush effects once per turn.

### 7.1.10. Achromatic {#7.1.10.-achromatic}

	Cards with Achromatic have the following Effect text:  
	“![][image6]This Card’s Hand Cost can be paid with any Symbol.”

	Cards with Achromatic may not be used as Hand Cost for other cards as though they have every Symbol. The benefit of Achromatic is only for paying the Hand Cost of the card with Achromatic.

### 7.1.11. Shift {#7.1.11.-shift}

	Cards with Shift are always treated as non-Effect cards in all areas. The Effect included in the red parenthesis **( )** after the Shift keyword may not be used unless gained specifically through another Effect. These properties are mechanical, and may not be negated or changed by Effects. The Effect in red parenthesis **( )** may still be negated or changed by Effects.

### 7.1.12. Calling {#7.1.12.-calling}

Cards with Calling have the following effect text:  
“![][image6]Valid: If the number of cards in your Discard Pile is equal to or greater than this effect’s Calling Value, gain the following effect:”

Gaining an effect through Calling is mandatory. Effects gained through Calling will indicate whether they are optional.

If an effect gained through Calling is added to the Chain, and before that effect resolves, the number of cards in the controller of that effect’s Discard Pile is reduced below the Calling Value, the effect will do nothing when it resolves.

### 7.1.13. Flood {#7.1.13.-flood}

When an effect directs a player to Flood, they perform the following:  
	“Move a card of your choice from your opponent’s Discard Pile to their Essence area. If they do not have a card in their Discard Pile to move, move the top card of their deck to their Essence area instead.”

	When Flood is indicated, if it is followed by a number, e.g. **Flood 2**, multiple cards are moved simultaneously. If an effect directs a player to Flood more cards than the opposing player has in their Discard Pile, as many cards as possible are moved from the Discard Pile before the remaining number of cards for Flood are moved from the top of the deck.

	Flood is not considered a Charge effect.

### 7.1.14. Ascend {#7.1.14.-ascend}

Cards with Ascend have the following effect text:  
“![][image6]: This card’s Summon/Play does not count toward the one Summon/Strategy card per turn limit.”

Cards with Ascend may be played before or after a player has used their one Summon/Strategy card for the turn.

Players may Summon or play as many cards with Ascend as they would like in a turn.

## 7.2. Effect Types {#7.2.-effect-types}
