While most Strategy and Ability cards apply their Effects on play before moving to the essence area as a single use, Effects with more flexible applications have their timings broken down into three categories:  
Activate \- Effects are used when the controller chooses  
Trigger \- Effects that may only be used when something happens  
Ongoing \- passive Effects that are always applied as long as the card is in play or meets specific requirements

These Effects can be found on any type of card and will specify if they are activated or used in any out of play areas. If the Effect doesn’t specify where it activates, the card must be in play in order to be used.

### 7.2.1. Activate Effects {#7.2.1.-activate-effects}

Activate Effects are used whenever the player controlling the card chooses to. They always start or add to a Chain, and as long as the timing is correct, Activate Effects may be added to any Chain not currently resolving.

There are three kinds of Activate Effects:  
![][image9]\- The card may use the Effect once during the current turn.  
![][image10]\- The card may use the Effect once during the current turn. The player using the Effect may not use the same Effect of any other copies of the card for the remainder of the turn.  
![][image11] \- The card may use the Effect once during the current turn. The player using the Effect may not use the same Effect of any other copies of the card for the remainder of the **game**.

The limitations of these Activate Effects are put in place as soon as the Effect is placed on the Chain regardless of whether the Effect resolves successfully.

When card text refers to/targets/names/etc. ![][image9] Effects, it also does so to ![][image10] and ![][image11] effects.

#### 7.2.1.1. Activate Syntax {#7.2.1.1.-activate-syntax}

All Activate Effects follow the same syntax: Timing, Cost, and Effects.

**Timings**  
The Timing of an Activate Effect indicates when you may use the Effect and is broken down into a sequence of whether the Effect is Valid (if specified), on whose turn it may be used (if specified), and which phase or phases of a turn it may be used. They are displayed in that order in brackets “\[ \]”. 

Here’s an example of what a timing bracket might look like:  
\[Valid|Your Turn|Main|EOA\]

The **Valid** portion indicates that a Character card in Injured status can still use this Effect. If this is missing, the Effect isn’t Valid and can only be used when the Character is Healthy.   
The **Your Turn** in the example specifies that the Effect may only be used during your turn. It could also say **Opponent’s Turn**, or it won’t specify which turn at all, in which case it can be used during either.  
The **Main|EOA** of the example indicates that the Effect may be used during either the Main or Exchange of Ability phases. Any phase can be a possible timing window for an Activate Effect.

Here’s another example of a timing bracket of an Activate Effect:  
\[EOA\]  
In this case, the Effect isn’t Valid, so it can only be used if the character is Healthy. The turn isn’t specified, so it may be used during either. Finally, the Exchange of Ability is the only listed phase, so the Effect may only be used then.

**Cost**  
All activate Effects indicate a Cost in bold after the timing brackets and before a colon “:”. A Cost may direct you to perform a specific action, or it may simply indicate Essence to be paid with Symbols. Some cards may include both. Costs are always paid as the card Effect is added to a Chain.

**Effect**  
Everything after the colon “:” of the Cost is considered a part of the Effect and is applied when the card resolves on the Chain.   
If a card refers to a Target in its Effect text, that target needs to be declared before paying Cost.

#### 7.2.1.2. Examples of Activate Syntax {#7.2.1.2.-examples-of-activate-syntax}

Here are a few examples of activate Effects:

0004 Smallfry

The ![][image10] Symbol indicates that only one copy of Smallfry’s Effect may be activated this turn. The timing bracket indicates it may only be used during the active player’s main phase, and the Cost to activate the Effect in bold directs the player to Move Smallfry from the Hand to the Essence Area. Since the Effect specifies moving the card from the Hand to the Essence area as part of the Cost, Smallfry does not need to be in play to activate this Effect.

0068 Astrophanese

The ![][image9] Symbol indicates that multiple copies of Astrophanes can use this Effect once each per turn. The timing bracket is missing “Valid” so it can’t be activated or resolved if Astrophanes is Injured. The timing brackets don’t specify which player’s turn it can be used on, so it may be used on either player’s turn. It can only be used during the Exchange of Ability step. The Cost to activate the Effect is to Move 2 Plasma Essence from the Essence Area to the Discard Pile. Since no part of the Activate Effect of Astrophanese refers to an out of play area as part of its use, Astrophanes must be in play to activate this ability.  

### 7.2.2. Trigger Effects {#7.2.2.-trigger-effects}

Trigger Effects activate in response to a condition being met. If a Trigger Effect’s condition is met while building a chain (such as in response to a player playing a card), the Trigger Effect will add itself to the Chain. If the Trigger condition is met in the middle of resolving a Chain, the Effect will wait for that Chain to finish and then activate, starting a new Chain. As long as the card is where it needs to be when the Trigger condition is met, it can always activate, and cannot “miss” timing, even if the card with the Trigger Effect is no longer in a public area of play.

![][image12] \- The trigger Effect may be activated every time the trigger is met. Some trigger Effects will specify that they are once per turn.  
![][image13] \- The trigger Effect may be activated once during the turn only across all copies of the same card.  
![][image14] \- The trigger Effect may be activated once during the turn across all copies of the same card. The player using the Effect may not use the same Effect of any other copies of the card for the remainder of the **game**.

The limitations of these Trigger Effects are put in place as soon as the Effect is placed on the Chain regardless of whether the Effect resolves successfully.

When card text refers to/targets/names/etc. ![][image12] Effects, it also does so to ![][image13] and ![][image14] effects.

#### 7.2.2.1. Trigger Syntax {#7.2.2.1.-trigger-syntax}

If a Trigger Effect doesn’t have a Cost to activate, the activation conditions will be found at the beginning of the Effect text. If a Trigger Effect includes “you may” after its conditions, the player controlling the card may elect not to activate the Effect. **If a Trigger Effect does not include “you may”, it is not optional and must be activated at the first legal opportunity.**

If a Trigger Effect has a Cost to activate, the condition for the Effect to be met is written in brackets “\[ \]”, the Cost of the Effect written in bold and a colon “:”, and followed by the Effect. Trigger Effects with Costs are always optional. Character card triggers will also indicate if they are Valid.

#### 7.2.2.2. Examples of Trigger Effect Syntax {#7.2.2.2.-examples-of-trigger-effect-syntax}

Here are a few examples of Trigger Effect Syntax:

0085 Samanosuke

The timing bracket indicates that the Effect is Valid, so it may be activated or resolved if Samanosuke is Injured. The activation condition indicates that the Trigger Effect activates when Samanosuke is sent out to Attack. The bold text after the brackets indicates that the Cost to activate the Effect is to Move 1 Character card with {Weapon} from the Discard Pile to the bottom of the deck.

0089 Carnodile

The timing bracket doesn’t indicate that Carnodile is Valid, so if it becomes Injured before the Effect resolves, it will do nothing. The timing bracket indicates that the activation condition for the Effect is putting Carnodile In Play. The Essence Symbols before the colon “:” indicate that in order to activate, the player must pay 2 Water or 2 Terra to activate.

0036 Krakoon

There is no timing window in Krakoon’s Effect, nor is there any bold text, so this Effect has no Cost to activate. The beginning of the Effect indicates the trigger condition “When this Character card is Summoned,”. The remainder of the Effect does not include “you may” so the controller must target 1 Character and place a Poison Counter on it. If Krakoon is the only Character In Play, the controller must select Krakoon.

#### 

#### 

#### 7.2.2.3. Multiple Trigger Effects with the Same Timing {#7.2.2.3.-multiple-trigger-effects-with-the-same-timing}

When multiple Trigger Effects would activate at the same time, they form a Chain in the order their conditions were met. If their conditions were met at the same time, they are added to the Chain in the order of the player controlling their Effect’s choosing (regardless of whether an Effect is mandatory or optional), starting with all of the Turn Player’s Effects followed by all of the Non-Turn Player’s Effects.

If a Trigger Effect can be added to a Chain at the same time an Activate Effect, Ability Card or Strategy Card could be added to the Chain, the Trigger Effect must be added first.

If a Non-Turn player’s Trigger Effect would activate and the Turn player has no Trigger Effects to activate within the same Timing window, the Non-Turn Player’s Trigger Effect is activated and placed on the Chain even if that player does not have Priority.

If an optional Trigger Effect’s timing is met, the player that would activate the Effect must address whether they will do so. If they choose not to, they may not use the Effect later in the Chain or turn unless the Trigger Effect’s timing is met again.

#### 7.2.2.4. Choosing Not to Use Optional Trigger Effects {#7.2.2.4.-choosing-not-to-use-optional-trigger-effects}

If the timing requirement to activate an optional Trigger Effect is met, the player controlling that Effect must address whether they are choosing to activate it or not. If they elect not to activate the Effect, they may not activate it later in the Chain unless the timing requirement to activate the Effect is met again.

#### 7.2.2.5. Privately Activated Triggers {#7.2.2.5.-privately-activated-triggers}

If movement of a card within private game zones would cause a Trigger effect to meet its activation condition, that Trigger effect may be used by revealing the card in its private area, provided all players are made aware of the movement of cards.

	*Example:* 0230 Dalgaa *may give \+1/+1 to a Character when it is moved to the bottom of the deck. If Dalgaa is moved from the hand or top of the player’s deck to the bottom of the deck, the player may reveal Dalgaa from the bottom of the deck and declare the activation of its Trigger effect before returning Dalgaa to the bottom of the deck.*

### 7.2.3. Ongoing Effects {#7.2.3.-ongoing-effects}

![][image15]  
Ongoing Effects do not start Chains and cannot be Chained to. When a card with an Ongoing Effect doesn’t specify its condition, the card must be in play to apply its Effect. When it enters or leaves play, it immediately applies or stops applying its Ongoing Effects, even in the middle of a Chain.

Cards with ![][image16] work the same as other Ongoing effects with the exception that multiple copies may not stack the effect on top of another. The effect will continue to apply as long as at least 1 source of the effect remains in the area it needs to be to apply.

When card text refers to/targets/names/etc. ![][image15] Effects, it also does so to ![][image16] Effects.

#### 7.2.3.1. Ongoing Syntax {#7.2.3.1.-ongoing-syntax}

Ongoing Effects do not follow a uniform syntax. Each Ongoing Effect will describe its context and application on an individual basis.

#### 7.2.3.2. Ongoing Applications During Chain Resolution {#7.2.3.2.-ongoing-applications-during-chain-resolution}

If an Ongoing Effect directs a player to perform an action such as moving a card from one game zone to another or removing a Counter, that action is performed immediately as directed, even if other Effects are resolving or waiting to resolve.

*Example: 0042 Oceanic Abyss has an Ongoing Effect that allows a player to Move a character to the Essence area instead of the Discard Pile. If 0036 Stake Gun used by a {Slayer} character deals enough Damage to the character to Discard it, when resolving that part of the Effect, that character will Move to the Essence area due to the Ongoing Effect of Oceanic Abyss, and afterward Stake Gun would continue to resolve and Discard cards from the top of the deck.*

## 

## 7.3. Effects of In Play Cards Must Remain in Play {#7.3.-effects-of-in-play-cards-must-remain-in-play}

If an Activate or Trigger Effect requires a card to be In Play to be activated (meaning it does not specify where it activates), that card must remain In Play at the time of resolution in order to apply its Effect. If it is no longer In Play at the time of resolution, the Effect does nothing.

The exception to this rule is when a card Moves *itself* to a not In Play area as a part of the card’s Effect or Cost.

*Example: Both 0023 Necrosurgeon and 0025 Lurking In The Depths require you to Move them to the Essence Area to activate their Effects.*

## 

## 

##

## 7.4. Effects that Direct Player to “Pay”

When an effect directs a player to “Pay”, followed by one or more Essence symbols, it is directing the player to move the indicated Essence to their Discard Pile, similar to paying the Essence Cost of an Ability Card. These “Pay” directions are optional, but are often followed by the “and if you do” clause, causing the remainder of the following effect to do nothing if not paid. Paying Essence for these effects are not Costs.

*Example: 0003* Cayne Gunner*’s Expert effect indicates to Pay 2 Neutral Essence, and if the player does, deal 1 Damage to the target. The payment of 2 Essence is optional, but the remainder of the Expert effect will do nothing if the 2 Essence is not paid.*  
![][image17]

## 

## 7.5. Effect Negation {#7.5.-effect-negation}

While an Effect is Negated, the Effect may not be activated or applied.

Ongoing Effects will no longer apply for the duration of the Negation. 

Any Effects on a Chain that are Negated will do nothing when resolving. 

If a card has multiple Effects, each one may be Negated individually. If an Effect that would apply Negation does not specify an individual Effect, all Effect texts of the card are Negated.

Costs, Characteristics, or Attributes of a Card cannot be Negated.

If a card with a Negated Effect has a Trigger Effect with an activation requirement that was met while the Effect was Negated, the Effect may not be activated even if the Effect is no longer Negated when the Effect would be placed on the Chain, as the text describing the activation condition was Negated.

If a card with a once per turn/game Effect has its Effect text Negated when it resolves, it is still considered to have been used for the purposes of activation limits. If the text is no longer Negated afterward, the Effect is still considered the same one that was used and may not be used again.

If an Effect indicates that it Negates a Card/Effect but does not specify the duration, the Effect is only Negated until the Chain fully resolves.

If an Effect is already negated, it cannot be negated a second time.

When a Negation Effect indicates it Negates an Effect on a Chain, it is referring to that specific instance of the Effect placed on the Chain and not the Effect text of the card that put it in place. 

*Example: A player puts In Play a \<Micromon\> Character and activates 0002 Unexpected Encounter’s Trigger Effect to place 1 Counter on the card and the Effect is Negated by 0065 Raikiri. If the controller of Unexpected Encounter puts in play another \<Micromon\> Character, they may activate Unexpected Encounter again and resolve it successfully.*

## 7.6. Lingering Effects {#7.6.-lingering-effects}

	If an Effect specifies its duration (during this turn, this turn, until the start/end of a turn, etc.), once that Effect resolves successfully, it will continue to apply even if the original source of the Effect leaves play or has its Effect Negated.

	*Example: 0063 Sasaki is in play while its controller Discards the top card of the opponent’s deck. Sasaki adds its Trigger Effect to the chain and resolves it successfully to gain \+2/+0 for the turn. Afterward, Player B uses 0005 Scourge of the Sea to Negate Sasaki’s Effect. Since Sasaki’s Effect has already resolved successfully and it specifies how long the Effect lasts for, Sasaki will continue to get \+2/+0 for the turn.*

## 7.7. Effect Targets {#7.7.-effect-targets}

If an Effect refers to a Target, the controller of that Effect must declare a legal target in order to activate the Effect. Targets can’t be changed after being designated.

If an Effect refers to multiple Targets, the same Target may not be selected more than once.

	When resolving an Effect that Targets, at least one of the Targets must still be a legal Target at the time of resolution, otherwise the entire effect fails and is not applied. If at least 1 of the declared Targets is still a Target at the time of resolution, the Effect will resolve and do as much as it can.

An Effect may Target a card if it meets the Target requirements even if that Effect would not accomplish any observable change to the game state.  
	*Example: An Effect indicates it Targets “1 Character” and Heals it. Because the Target requirement is “1 Character”, you may Target a Character that is already Healthy, even if you can’t Heal an already Healthy Character.*

## 7.8. Multiple Contradicting Effects {#7.8.-multiple-contradicting-effects}

When multiple effects are applied that contradict the same rule, the effects are applied based on which player controls which effect and which player is the turn player:

1\) **Both players are applying an effect that alters the same rule:**  
	  
The Turn player's Effect must take precedence, and any Effect(s) controlled by the non-turn player that alters the same rule is ignored.  
	*Example: Player B controls 0054 Pollux Pride. During the EOA step, Player A uses 0077 Fire Crystal Heat Aura. Both cards affect where a card goes when it moves to the Discard Pile. If Player A is the turn player, the card Discarded by Fire Crystal Heat Aura will go underneath the controller's Field card. If player B is the turn player, the card Discarded by Fire Crystal Heat Aura will move to the Expel area.*

2\) **A single player is applying multiple Effects that alter the same rule:**  
	  
The player controlling the effects chooses which one to apply and which one to ignore on an individual basis.  
	*Example: Player A controls an effect that states "All cards moved to the Discard Pile are moved to the Expel area instead" as well as an effect that states "All cards moved to the Discard Pile are moved to the Essence area instead". When Player A would Discard multiple cards at the same time, each card may be moved to either the Essence area or Expel area. They do not all need to be moved to the same area.*

	The order of which cards or effects are applied does not influence which effect takes precedence.

## 7.9. Repeatable Effects {#7.9.-repeatable-effects}

When an effect directs a player to repeat the directions of an effect, the direction to repeat the effect itself is not repeated. Effects will only be repeated as often as explicitly indicated in the effect text. 

# GLOSSARY {#glossary}

[**\+1+1 Counter**](#6.2.6.-+1/+1-counters-and--1/-1-counters) **\-** A Counter placed on Character cards that increase that Character’s Stat Values.  
[**Attach**](#6.1.3.-attached-cards-and-cards-placed-underneath-cards) **\-** Attached cards are placed underneath another card with one stacked on the other. Attached cards are not considered in play, even if the card they are Attached to is. Attached cards don’t do anything by themselves unless specified by their card text and are Moved to the Discard pile when the card they are Attached to leaves play.  
When an In-Play card is Attached to another card, it leaves play and any Effects (including the Attached card’s) that would activate due to a card leaving play may be activated.  
[**Attack**](#5.5.1.-attack-step) **\-** Sent to the battlefield by the turn player.  
[**Battle Reward (BR)**](#battle-reward-area) **\-** Cards in the Battle Reward zone. When a player wins any number of Battle Rewards, their opponent Moves that many cards from the top of the deck to their play area’s Battle Reward zone face down. When the showdown results in a “Battle Reward”, the Attacker wins 1 Battle Reward. Shortened to BR.  
[**Block**](#5.5.2.-block-step) **\-** Sent to the battlefield by the non-turn player.  
[**Camouflage**](#7.1.2.-camouflage) **\-** Keyword. Cards with Camouflage may be Summoned from the Essence Area as though they were in your Hand. Can’t be combined with other effects that put in play cards.  
Charge \- To move to the Essence Area. Players may Charge cards from their Hand during their Main Phase while they have Priority. Card effects might Charge cards from other areas.  
[**Cost**](#6.1.2.-costs) **\-** A requirement to activate Effects. Costs are paid by spending resources like Essence, tokens, coins etc, or moving cards from one area of play to another. Once paid, Costs are not returned to the player who paid them, even if their Effect doesn’t work out the way they wanted.  
[**Counter**](#6.3.4.-counter-strategy-cards) **(strategy cards) \-** Keyword. Strategy cards with Counter can only be played during an opponent’s main phase.  
[**Counter**](#2.2.2.-counters) **(general term) \-** Game pieces like coins placed on cards to track or be referenced by Effects. Counters don’t do anything by themselves.  
[**Damage**](#6.2.4.-damage) **\-** When receiving Damage, Healthy Characters are changed to Injured and Injured Characters are Discarded. 2 or more Damage will Discard the Character outright.  
[**Detach**](#6.1.3.1.-detaching-cards) **\-** To move an Attached card to the owner’s Discard Pile.  
[**Discard**](#6.-card-properties) **\-** To Move to the Discard pile.  
[**Discard Pile (DP)**](#discard-pile-\(shortened-to-dp\)) \- Area where cards go when they are no longer used. Shortened to DP.  
[**Effect**](#7.-effect-texts) **\-** The part of a card’s text that does something that can affect the outcome of the game. Effects sometimes have Costs or Requirements that need to be met to use them.  
[**Expel**](#expel-area) \- To Move to the Expel Area. Cards that are Expelled are generally more difficult to access.  
[**Expert**](#7.1.6.-expert) **\-** Keyword. When resolving the Effect of an Ability card with Expert, if the User meets the Expert requirements, the additional Effect is applied in addition to the original Effect, although some Expert Effects may specify they replace the original Effect instead.  
[**Hand Cost**](#6.1.2.2.-hand-cost) **\-** When Summoning, Playing Strategies, or using Transformation, Hand Cost must be paid by moving cards of a matching Symbol from the Hand to the Essence Area.  
[**Heal**](#6.2.3.-healthy-and-injured-states) **\-** To change a character from Injured (Horizontal) to Healthy (Vertical). You can’t Heal a character that is already Healthy.   
[**Healthy**](#6.2.3.-healthy-and-injured-states) **\-** An unDamaged character in the vertical position. If this character receives one Damage it will become Injured.  
[**Injure**](#6.2.3.-healthy-and-injured-states) **\-** To change the character from Healthy (Vertical) to Injured (Horizontal). You can’t Injure a character that is already Injured.  
[**Injured**](#6.2.3.-healthy-and-injured-states) \- A character in the horizontal position. If this character receives one Damage it will be Discarded. Effect text of Injured characters may not be activated, resolved, or otherwise applied unless that Effect includes: “Valid”.  
**Move** \- A card transferred from one area to another. When a card is Moved, it is not considered to be drawn, Expelled or Discarded, but drawing cards, Discarding cards or Expelling cards are all examples of Movement.  
[**Name:**](#6.2.5.1.-“name:”-characteristics) **\-** A special characteristic. Character cards with this are considered to have the name designated in all areas in addition to their printed name.  
[**Negate**](#7.5.-effect-negation) **\-** While an Effect is Negated, the Effect may not be activated or applied. Ongoing Effects will no longer apply for the duration of the Negation, and any Effects on a Chain that are Negated will do nothing instead of apply their Effects. If a once per turn/game Effect is Negated when it resolves, it is still considered to have been used for the purposes of activation limits.  
[**Outstanding Victory**](#5.5.4.-showdown-step) **\-** A result of the Showdown. When a Team’s Team Power is greater than the opposing Team’s by 5 or more. The losing Team suffers 2 Damage to their Lead Character and 1 Damage to all Supporting Characters.  
[**Outstanding Battle Reward**](#5.5.4.-showdown-step) **\-** When the showdown results in an “Outstanding Battle Reward”, the Attacker wins 2 Battle Rewards.  
[**Opposing**](#5.5.2.-block-step) **\-** When Attacking, all of the characters Blocking the character’s Team. When Blocking, all of the characters in the Attacking Team Blocked by the character.  
[**Permanent**](#7.1.5.-permanent) **\-** Strategy cards with this keyword are Moved to the owner’s kingdom instead of the essence area after resolving.  
[**Permanent (x)**](#6.3.3.-permanent-\(x\)-strategy-cards) **\-** With x \= the number on each respective card, Strategy cards with this keyword are Moved to the owner’s kingdom instead of the essence area after resolving. X Permanent Counters are placed onto the card, with one removed at the start of each of the owner’s turns. After the last Permanent Counter is removed, the card is Moved to the owner’s essence area.  
[**Permanent Counter**](#6.3.3.-permanent-\(x\)-strategy-cards) **\-** A Counter placed on a Permanent (X) Strategy Card when the card is put into play. Effects that affect Counters may be used on Permanent Counters, but Effects that affect Permanent Counters may only affect Permanent Counters.  
[**Put in play**](#3.1.-in-play-areas-\(highlighted-in-red\)) **\-** A general term for a card moving from an “out of play” area to an “in play” one, usually through a card Effect. Summoning is also considered putting in play, but putting a character into play is not Summoning. Unlike playing cards with once per turn mechanics, when a card is put in play, the player doing so ignores Turn and Hand Cost.   
[**Requirement**](#6.4.3.-requirements) **\-** Ability Cards with Requirements cannot be used unless the User has the indicated trait. Requirements may include Names, Hand Costs, Turn Costs, Characteristics, Attributes, specified Stat Values or Symbols in any combination.  
[**Showdown**](#5.5.4.-showdown-step) \- A step in the Battle Phase where Team Power is calculated and the result of battle is determined. Possible results include Victory, Outstanding Victory, Stalemate, Battle Reward, Outstanding Battle Reward.  
[**Stalemate**](#5.5.4.-showdown-step) **\-** A result of the showdown. When both Teams have the same Team Power, the Team Lead of both Teams takes 1 Damage.  
[**Stand-by**](#5.2.2.1.-stand-by-characters) **\-** Not on the battlefield. When a card on the Battlefield is made stand-by, it is Moved to a new Team in its controller’s kingdom. When multiple characters in the same Team are made stand-by, they are Moved into a new Team together. Stand-by characters cannot be the Users of ability cards and any unresolved ability cards that character was using resolve without Effect. A character not on the battlefield cannot be made Stand-by.  
[**Stat Values**](#6.2.2.-stat-values) **\-** The numbers on the lower right (or lower left if Injured) corner of the card indicating the Lead and Support Values.  
[**Summon**](#5.3.2.-main-phase-as-the-turn-player) \- Once per turn during their turn’s Main Phase, a player may select a Character Card in their Hand whose Turn Cost is equal to or greater than their Turn Marker, and if the character has a Hand Cost of 1 or more, Move that many cards of a matching Symbol from their Hand to their Essence Area. The Character Card they selected is then put in play to the player’s Kingdom.  
[**Symbol**](#6.1.1.-symbols) **\-** Suit of the card found in the upper-right Hand corner. If a card has multiple Symbols, it is considered to have all Symbols at the same time.  
[**Team**](#5.4.-organization-phase) **\-** A stack of character cards that combine their Lead and Support values.  
[**Team Power**](#5.5.4.-showdown-step) **\-** The total number of the Lead character’s Lead value and the Supporting characters’ Support values.  
[**Team Leader**](#5.5.1.-attack-step) **\-** The character card at the top of a stack of cards in a Team. A character in a Team by itself is a Team Leader.  
[**Team Support**](#5.5.1.-attack-step) **\-** The character cards under the top card of a stack of cards in a Team.  
[**Transformation**](#7.1.1.-transformation) **\-** Keyword. During your main phase, if you control a character that meets the requirements of a card’s Transformation keyword, you may put in play that Character card with Transformation from your Hand with the required Character Attached. When you do, the character with Transformation gains the Effect text of any Character cards that were Attached to perform Transformation. When using Transformation, your turn marker must be equal to or greater than the card’s printed entrance Cost \-1 and you must pay the card’s printed Hand Cost \-1 (to a minimum of 0). This is also considered a Summon but doesn’t count toward the 1 Summon per turn limit. Characters with Transformation also have Unique in all areas.  
[**Turn Cost**](#6.1.2.1.-turn-cost) **\-** When Summoning, Playing Strategies, or using Transformation, the Player’s Turn Marker must be equal to or greater than the Turn Cost of the card.  
[**Unique**](#7.1.3.-unique) **\-** Keyword. Cards with the Unique may not enter play if a card with the same print number is already in play.   
[**User**](#6.4.2.-ability-card-users) \- The Character card on the Battlefield designated to using an Ability Card. If the User leaves the Battlefield before the Ability Card resolves, the Ability Card won’t apply its Effect.  
[**Valid**](#6.2.3.1-injured-character-effects) **\-** Allows for Effects to be usable when a character is Injured. When a character is in Injured status, its Effects are not usable, but if an Effect begins with “Valid:”, the Effect may still be used.  
[**Victory**](#5.5.4.-showdown-step) \- A result of the Showdown when a Team’s Team Power is greater than the Opposing Team, but not greater by 5\. The losing Team suffers 1 Damage to their Lead Character.
